pmc BMC Genomics BMC Genomics 32 bmcgeno BMC Genomics 1471-2164 BMC PMC12482561 PMC12482561.1 12482561 12482561 41023610 10.1186/s12864-025-12023-9 12023 1 Software SoMaCX: a complex generative genome modeling framework Becker Timothy James tbecker@conncoll.edu https://ror.org/01hpqfm28 grid.254656.6 0000 0001 2343 1311 Department of Computer Science, Connecticut College, 29 9 2025 2025 26 478389 853 2 1 2025 20 8 2025 29 09 2025 01 10 2025 01 10 2025 © The Author(s) 2025 2025 https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0/ Open Access http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0/ Background Somatic structural variations (SVs) are commonly observed in cancer tissue, but remain challenging to discover with short and long read sequencing due to tumor heterogeneity and other technical sequencing factors. Only SVs with a sufficient fraction of reads spanning the event will be detectable, while issues like chromothripsis increase the complexity and resulting interpretation significantly. Because structural variation is difficult to measure and reproduce in vivo, it is logical to make use of simulation frameworks to determine realistic system limitations. Our generative modeling approach called soMaCX uses distributions from data to empower simulations that approach real data. Results Our generative framework includes mechanisms for biological conservation in the germline as well as tissue composition in the somatic along with regional distribution controls and complex SV generation that is not available in other systems. The output of this system is FASTA format which can then be used as input to any downstream read simulator making Illumina, PacBio, 10X genomics, Oxford-Nanopore and Bionano FASTQ data files which are further processed to become standard BAM files for SV calling. Conclusions The soMaCX framework provides superior generative modeling-based performance when compared to other simulation frameworks with respect to real data. Our open-source method introduces an important conceptual element to simulation by utilizing biological relevant regions (genes and regulatory elements) as the distribution controls along with the biological modulation of known pathways (end-joining) leading to more detailed and realistic simulated genomes. By designing a generative method to explore the most difficult genomic conditions, we provide a means to measure germline variation calling performance and to calibrate the results for rare variants needed in the clinical setting. We provide a python 3 implementation at: https://github.com/timothyjamesbecker/somacx Supplementary Information The online version contains supplementary material available at 10.1186/s12864-025-12023-9. Keywords Next generation sequencing Genome simulation Somatic simulation Generative modeling FASTA generation. National Institutes of Health R03DE033083 Becker Timothy James pmc-status-qastatus 0 pmc-status-live yes pmc-status-embargo no pmc-status-released yes pmc-prop-open-access yes pmc-prop-olf no pmc-prop-manuscript no pmc-prop-legally-suppressed no pmc-prop-has-pdf yes pmc-prop-has-supplement yes pmc-prop-pdf-only no pmc-prop-suppress-copyright no pmc-prop-is-real-version no pmc-prop-is-scanned-article no pmc-prop-preprint no pmc-prop-in-epmc yes issue-copyright-statement © BioMed Central Ltd., part of Springer Nature 2025 Introduction Cancer evolution literature has shown that less than 5% of a survival advantage is offered to oncogenic regions through normal environmental exposure like ultra-violet radiation, but these external effects can create selective advantage to those cells that have the oncogenic alterations. This in turn can cause feedback deriving more variation due to loss of function with DNA repair mechanisms [ 1 2 3 4 6 de novo 7 The system works by first generating the starting point which is a germline genome (two FASTA files for the maternal and paternal lines) that may also have de novo  Fig. 1 Clonal Evolution in the somatic genome can either be simulated by using a JSON configuration file as shown above or can also be simulated using a set of branching and decay parameters ( for branching, for decay). This allows users to build (A) sub-clonal structures (B) cancer stem cell structures Genomic variation rates for every SV type are established by a two-dimensional vector with b )) 8 (1–5)  Fig. 2 SV types include pre-SV substitutions (SNV, MNV), insertions, deletion, duplications, inversions, translocations and finally post-SV substitutions. This allows the user to have SNV and MNV that are in and out of linkage to the DEL, DUP, INV, INS, TRA events. The visualization shows an example of the chance of an SV event per base-pair (the Y axis) along with the chance for a given size (the X axis). These distributions are set within the JSON file. Defaults are included in the soMaCX distribution that are based on the 1000 Genomes Phase 3 rates detected using the SVE and FusorSV framework The soMaCX framework allows simulation of healthy individuals that have properties and rates similar to the 1000 genomes Phase 3 or Phase 4 samples (for example) [ 4 6 6 9 10 https://github.com/timothyjamesbecker/somacx Genome consortium efforts such as the 1000 Genomes project have estimated that a typical human genome contains 2.1–2.5 thousand SVs (greater than 50 base pairs), affecting ~ 20 million base pairs (bp), or ~ 5 times that of normally affected SNVs [ 2 4 6 11 11 12 11 13 Although many read simulators have been developed in the past ten years, none have focused on the ability to include complex SVs (along with linked and unlinked SNVs) using biologically relevant structures or have specifically targeted and modeled major drivers of those SVs (end-joining pathways) which are related to replication-based perturbations [ 14 15 14 16 DNA breakage and repair Unlike germline genomes, cancer genomes are under selective pressure either before or after treatment in the form of pathway impairments and double stranded DNA breaks. To repair the damage, cells will employ homologous mediated repair, or homologous recombination, by utilizing the corresponding sequence of the site of damage on the undamaged sister chromatid to allow for precise repair. Homologous mediated repair can only occur after DNA has replicated in S phase and occurs in G2 and only if the pathway is intact [ 1 Non-homologous end joining (NHEJ) can occur before S phase in G1, where the break is ligated by protein machinery including the Ku70/80 heterodimer as well as protein kinases and additional ligases. NHEJ is particularly error prone, and initially small deletions are made in the end breaks before ligation. Disruption to both processes can result in chromosomal aberrations such as inversions and deletions and other replication errors observed in chromosomes after progression of malign tumor formation [ 14 16 1 An alternate form of NHEJ, microhomology-mediated end joining (MMEJ), requires protein machinery similar to homologous mediated repair, and is Ku70/80 independent [ 17 17 18 One prominent cause of cell immortality in cancer is apoptotic dysfunction [ 1 1 1 A complete loss or gain of a chromosome, known as aneuploidy, has also been shown in cancer cell lines. This occurs during abnormal mitotic checkpoint (MITCP) function and spindle formation. When nuclear division proceeds, spindle formation through microtubule connection to the kinetochore is established in metaphase. If the spindle has not formed properly, chromosomes will not migrate to the proper pole and unequal chromosome number will result in the daughter cell. Normal function of the following genes has been shown in our dataset to be important for MITCP processing: BUB1, BUB1B, BUB3, CENPE, CDC20, CDH1, FZR1, MAD1L1, MAD2L1, MAD2L2, MAD2L1BP, MPEG1, PTTG1, RAE1 [ 19  Fig. 3 region (or gene list) distribution w Implementation To generate MNVs and SVs in controllable biological positions and with quantities and qualities that would reflect the full spectrum of healthy to diseased genomes, we employ a joint distribution with three components: positional, type and size, and then one additional dimension for somatic evolution (where the genome will vary from cell to cell). The positional distribution can be built with either gene lists or by using BED file coordinates directly with what we call classes that are names associate with a set of coordinates. For example, the default JSON file includes important classes such as “APOT” which is a gene list that keeps genes in the apoptosis pathway from being modified in the germline (0 chance of an SV event in that area). The positional distribution for n 3 m i 1 \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
