for the germline generation phase and finally Somatic: would denote somatic specific generation features. We took care to include most of the features listed in the SVEngine and SCNVsim papers to make the comparison table complete while adding implementation details in the bottom such as programming language and whether the system can currently be built or used which we thought was an important consideration from the user perspective Overall, soMaCX offers the feature set closest to current literature in the field of sequence variation and cancer sequencing. Additionally, we note that with soMaCX we implement a novel out of core algorithm that holds the original sequence and the currently generating clone sequence(s) and uses a genotype aware editing map to apply sequence variations from the left hand of the chromosome to the right which we call FASTA spooling (printing part of the somatic clone at a time like a printer). This allows our method to scale to extremely large clone numbers such as would be present in a single cell experiment. Several of the methods we looked at such as SCNVsim and Xome-Blender had limitations to clones less than 5 while in our experiment we explored around 25 which is the limit based on the coverage we chose. Current whole genome sequencing is limited with single cell experiments, but we envision this will be possible in the future and soMaCX will be capable of simulating those experiments without modification to algorithm or code implementation. SVEngine offer the next best set of features, but currently suffers from a lack of software maintenance where a modern system cannot build the software using the provided instructions nor run the software without modification to the depreciated python2 code [ 30 30 6 de novo 11 tHapMix includes a non-buildable dockerfile and a link to a functioning prebuilt image [ 31 12 15 Xome-Blender is a similar BAM mixing method to tHaPMix in that it takes input BAM files as input and then attempts to mix in new variations [ 32 SCNV uses functioning java code that runs and produces correct output, but the implementation has severe limitations such as a maximum of three clones and a total amount of variation for all three clones limited to 300 events [ 33 30 Varsim produces adequate germline sequence variation if it is given the exact set of events it should sample from such as a curated VCF file with all potential variations. The problem here though is that Varsim will not introduce de novo 15 Germline comparison with varsim  Table 2 JBPD euclidian distance SoMaCX G1K Varsim Note: Varsim randomly selects existing SVs in a non-generative manner from VCF file and so is incapable of de novo 5 For our first experiment we measured how close a set of soMaCX genomes could be to real germline data and contrast that to the same experiment with another simulation method which is shown in Table 2 21 We selected 15 samples from 1000 Genomes phase 3 and used the VCF files to generated 15 genomes with soMaCX set to hybrid mode (--g1k_sample) using the hgv37d preset al.ong with another 15 genomes using Varsim with the default setting and the same 15 sample input VCF files [ 15 1 2 23 22 24 2 We used a distance version of the Jaccard base-pair similarity (JBPS) metric for pairs of SV callers as described in the FusorSV manuscript method to construct a single distance value between any two datasets. This calculation is further detailed below in Eqs. ( 6 2 Individual SV caller performances for the 27-sample high coverage study in the FusorSV paper (middle row in Fig. 5 6 15 Somatic comparison with Xome-Blender  Table 3 JBPD euclidian distance Xome-blender does not generate germline or somatic SVs and then make a FASTA, instead it blends existing BAM files. The result is that very little variation is achieve and the input BAM file which were taken from 1000 genomes phase 4 where very similar to those germline samples. The TCRB samples have very large amount of SVs as they are measurably disrupted genomes For our second experiment (shown in Table 3 34  Fig. 5 (A): SV Caller performance by type for real human samples from the 1000 Genomes Phase 3 high coverage. 27 high coverage samples with 50 average coverage using PCR-free design, 250 bp average read length, 451 bp insert size mean, 125 bp insert size standard deviation. The upper row details two accuracy-based metrics which are the harmonic mean (F1 score) of the precision and recall on the x-axis and the Jaccard base pair similarity metric on the y-axis. The lower row shows the number of true calls against the number of calls made by each caller. (B) soMaCX hybrid normal germline simulation scores using the same format. (C) Varsim data scores are almost perfect and as a result makes this dataset further from the real one in than soMaCX. The visualizations of (A), (B) and (C) indicate differences in measurements of SV callers compared to the true known calls. Since (A) is real data, it represents the best estimates of the 1000 Genomes Phase 3 PCR-free high coverage data which may be missing some real calls due to the methodology that sought to control FDR (but didn’t use an orthogonal sequencing technology) JBPS and JBPD metric details The Jaccard base-pair similarity (J) metric counts the individual overlapping base-pair coordinates so that break point accuracy and other large copy number artifacts (like SV call multiplicity) are diminished, making the calculation close to sequence homology around the SV alleles. The Jaccard base-pair distance is simply 1.0-J which we denote as JBPD. A JBPD of 0.1 means that two call sets have 10% sequence divergence between the SV alleles. let \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
