n this work could be improved using the increased insertion discovery that the Human Genome Structural Variation project has discovered as the basis for better estimation of the insertion distribution [ 12 42 12 22 43 Because germline modeling is needed to create the somatic genomes, the soMaCX method is a natural mechanism to develop detailed phenotype related genetic disorder models where SNV, MNV and SV from studies such as the Gabriella Millers Kids First data portal can be used [ 44 5 6 Conclusions This paper details the important aspects of genome generation starting at the germline and how that can be used to simulate somatic tissues with clonal modeling through generative means. We introduced an important control structure which is missing in other simulation frameworks allowing for regional distributions that adhere to biological relevant functionality such as ensuring germline genomes do not have structural variants in the apoptosis pathway. This overlooked element has been generalized so that these regional controls (via gene set lists or BED files with enhancer regions) become an ideal method to perturb genomes and measure sequence variation detection accuracy in any given read platform. Additionally, there is no other simulation framework that offers the complexity of SVs where inversions can contain duplicated or deleted break ends as well as complex translocations or dispersed duplications. Given its flexibility, open-source code and extensibility from new data, this software framework will have broad application to the genomic community. Using ART simulated Illumina pair-end reads we showed that soMaCX simulated genomes are more similar to real data than other simulation frameworks and in turn can give a better estimate of system performance. For germline generation soMaCX can be used to model specific genetic disorders given a sample set of sufficient size where VCF and BED files can be used to allow multi-omic data to control the soMaCX distributions. For somatic tissues large studies can be used where allele frequencies can control the shape of each soMaCX simulated clonal tree offering a controllable but extremely complex simulation result. We included example scripts to process the soMaCX FASTA output into FASTQ for Illumina and PacBio data, but the user would need to expand our work in order to have working simulation for other read platforms such as Oxford Nanopore. Additionally, more complex structural variations beyond what we have implemented and detailed in our work would require future updates and careful planning since multiple overlapping SV alleles have not been formally defined or resolved theoretically. What this means is that measurement of overlapping SV events is not currently well defined and as a result our simulation tends to generate more well separated events (in coordinate space) other than the complex inversion and dispersed duplication SV types. There is room for future work to develop less ambiguous and more formal definitions of what exactly a copy number variation is versus a copy number aberration versus a deletion or duplication event. In our work we seek to carefully define and implement each of these possibilities so that the simulation framework can serve to benchmark a wide variety of platforms and algorithms such as CNVnator, ERDS, Ginko, SCICoNE, CHISEL and CNRein [ 36 45 49 50 Author contributions TJB completed all parts of the project. Funding This work was supported in part by NIH grant No. R03DE033083. Its contents are the sole responsibility of the authors and do not necessarily represent the views of the NIH. Supplementary Information Below is the link to the electronic supplementary material.  Supplementary Material 1 Abbreviations DEL deletion structural variation event DUP duplication structural variation event INV inversion structural variation event INS insertion structural variation event TRA translocation structural variation event NHEJ non-homologous end-join